/SCD/XXERASH/XX. This prayer helps us to get in touch with our gratitude for the
extraordinary, yet often overlooked daily workings of the world and
through them to recognize the insignificance of our own roles, to feel
humble. In becoming aware of our smallness, we become able to grasp our
relatedness to the All. This in turn makes it possible to overcome the lone-
liness of claiming we have all the answers and the anxiety of always need-
ing to be in control. At these moments the pain of our unfulfilled needs
is swept away in the wondrous goodness we feel in the world about us.
We give thanks.    /SC/XXS.P.W./XX/PR

/PR

/PR

/PR

/PG316/XX/PR

(/ITOn H/±anukah add:/XX For the miracles, for the redemption,/PR

for heroic acts, for saving deeds, for consolations,/PR

all of which you have enacted for our ancestors/PR

at this time of year in days gone by/PR

--as in the days of Matthew, son of Yoh/±anan,/PR

Hasmonean High Priest, and Matthewòs sons:/PR

a wicked Hellenistic government arose/PR

against your people Israel, forcing them to shun your Torah/PR

and to leave off from the laws your will ordained./PR

And you, in your abundant mercy,/PR

stood up for Israel in their hour of distress./PR

You pressed their claim, exacted justice for them./PR

You delivered armed might to the weak,/PR

the many to the power of the few,/PR

the wicked to the power of the just,/PR

the vicious to the power of those occupied with Torah./PR

You made known your name that day,/PR

and made it holy in your world./PR

And for your people Israel you enacted great deliverance,/PR

as in our own time. Afterward,/PR

your children came into your Templeòs inner room./PR

They cleared your sanctuary, purified your holy place,/PR

kindled lights inside your holy courtyards,/PR

and established these eight days of H/±anukah,/PR

for giving thanks and praise to your great name.)/PR

/PR

For all these things, your name be blessed/PR

and raised in honor always, sovereign of ours, forever./PR

